<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-285-955  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 285 955.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  Dec 1989 v62 n12 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Should HDTV sets have an open architecture? (high-definitiontelevision)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shandle, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A new battleground in the development of domestic high-definitiontelevision (HDTV) consists of competing proposals foropen-architecture, bus-based HDTV receivers versus a closed-boxmultiport receiver.andP;  Massachusetts Institute of Technology ProfWilliam F. Schreiber believes an open receiver architecture wouldenable easier and more cost-effective tailoring of the HDTVreceiver to desired services and to new standards andtechnologies.andP;  North American Philips chief scientist for advancedtelevision technology policy and planning and ElectronicIndustries Assn ATV Multiport Receiver Subcommittee Co-Chmn ArpadToth asserts that an open architecture display interface would betoo complex and expensive and that an ATV receiver would becompatible with a wide range of TV technologies.andP;  Both agree thatHDTV must be compatible with the current NTSC television standard.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ReceiversStandardsCompetitionProposalFuture TechnologiesOpen SystemsHigh definition television.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The multistandard solution. (chart)Person:    Schreiber, William F. (attitudes); Toth, Arpad (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>